    <commentid>2138128</commentid>
    <comment_count>0</comment_count>
    <who name="Sam Davis">sam.davis</who>
    <bug_when>2012-07-17 13:25:36 -0400</bug_when>
    <thetext>Can we make FillWidthLayout public?</thetext>
  </long_desc><long_desc isprivate="0" >
    <commentid>2138392</commentid>
    <comment_count>1</comment_count>
    <who name="Steffen Pingel">steffen.pingel</who>
    <bug_when>2012-07-18 04:50:13 -0400</bug_when>
    <thetext>It&apos;s intentionally not public to prevent reuse. It was designed for a very specific use case and makes assumptions about size constraints of its container. 

Sam, if you file bugs of this sort, please provide a quick rationale why you would want to do that.  Obviously it&apos;s trivial on a technical level but rather than making the class public we should consider generalizing the implementation and moving it into API if there are indeed good use cases for reuse.</thetext>
  </long_desc><long_desc isprivate="0" >
    <commentid>2139799</commentid>
    <comment_count>2</comment_count>
    <who name="Sam Davis">sam.davis</who>
    <bug_when>2012-07-20 16:33:44 -0400</bug_when>
    <thetext>We have a custom comments section and other places where we need to set the width to fill the editor page.</thetext>
  </long_desc><long_desc isprivate="0" >
    <commentid>2145273</commentid>
    <comment_count>3</comment_count>
    <who name="Steffen Pingel">steffen.pingel</who>
    <bug_when>2012-08-06 10:38:08 -0400</bug_when>
    <thetext>That sounds reasonable. If we can change FillWidthLayout so that it is safe to consume for third party extensions I&apos;m fine with moving it to an API package. I&apos;m -1 on making the current class public.</thetext>
  </long_desc><long_desc isprivate="0" >
    <commentid>2145382</commentid>
    <comment_count>4</comment_count>
    <who name="Sam Davis">sam.davis</who>
    <bug_when>2012-08-06 19:12:04 -0400</bug_when>
    <thetext>Ok, what would it take to make it safe? Is it just a question of adding some parameters so that extensions can specify their own size constraints?</thetext>
  </long_desc><long_desc isprivate="0" >
    <commentid>2172270</commentid>
    <comment_count>5</comment_count>
    <who name="Steffen Pingel">steffen.pingel</who>
    <bug_when>2012-10-16 05:38:03 -0400</bug_when>
    <thetext>That sounds good. It looks like widthHintMargin just needs a setter. Would be nice to also have a few tests and we should move the class into the commons if we make it API.</thetext>
